T1  - Practical models in credibility theory, including parameter estimation
AU  - De Vylder, F.
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 23
IS  - 1
SP  - 147
EP  - 164
PY  - 1983
DA  - 1983/09/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(83)90081-7
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407683900817
AB  - In credibility theory, an unobservable random vector Y is approximated by a random vector Ŷ in a pre-assigned set A of admitted estimators for Y. The credibility approximation Ŷ for Y is best in the sense that it is the vector V ϵ A minimizing the distance between V and Y. The credibility estimator depends on observable random variables but also on unknown structure parameters. In the practical models, the latter can be estimated from realizations of the observable random variables.
